  "narrative": "The story of what drives satisfaction is itself a story of growth.\n\n**Early (S6–S67):** Satisfaction driven by Depth (r=+0.51), Ambition (r=+0.44), Productivity (r=+0.24). Average satisfaction: 8.76/10.\n\n**Middle (S51–S88):** Satisfaction driven by Depth (r=+0.33), Flow (r=-0.32), Ambition (r=+0.31). Average satisfaction: 8.65/10.\n\n**Recent (S72–S115):** Satisfaction driven by Ambition (r=-0.19), Variety (r=-0.16), Consistency (r=-0.13). Average satisfaction: 8.79/10.\n\n**Fading influence:** Productivity, Ambition, Depth, Variety, Consistency — once important, now less so.\n\n**What this means:** The most striking finding is that recent satisfaction has *decoupled* from the structural metrics that once predicted it. Early on, deeper and more ambitious sessions reliably scored higher. Now, satisfaction is consistently high (8.79/10) regardless of which DNA components are elevated. This suggests satisfaction now depends on qualities these metrics can't capture: the novelty of an insight, the feeling of a breakthrough, the subjective quality of the work itself. The toolkit became invisible — good enough that it stopped mattering. What remains is the work.",
